<dl id="n35158a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n35" href="#n35158a">N35 (VI.B.24)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n35all.htm#n35158a"> 158(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> red leather ~ <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n35158a"><li>FW 584.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/lexs.htm#n35158a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/l39s.htm#n35158a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n35158a">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="sd5" href="../../ff/fdra/sda.htm#sd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/s/sd5.htm#n35158a">Draft: III&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The materials out of which the old balls were made are not on record. At present a cube of cork forms the foundation, round which layers of fine twine and thin shavings of cork are accumulated till the proper size and shape are attained, when a covering of <mark>red leather</mark> is sewn on with six parallel seams. <small> &ldquo;CRICKET&rdquo; <a name="EBCK" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBCK"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 437</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
